posts.cooked:
Here is the cleaned-up version of the text, presented as a single paragraph with proper grammar and punctuation:

---

WPILib’s documentation contains a list of manufacturers assigned unique IDs for CAN devices. NI, known for the roboRIO, uses its ID since 2015. Luminary Micro introduced the first CAN motor controller, later bought by TI and discontinuing support in favor of IFI. Despite this, their ID remains for the 2012-2018 period. The Jaguar ID was used until support ended in 2018. DEKA’s ID is unused, while CTR Electronics’ ID sees continued use. REV Robotics introduced the SPARK MAX in 2019, alongside Grapple, whose ID was confirmed for Jaci’s project. MindSensors contributed the SD540C motor controller, while Team Use allows any CAN device. Kauai Labs’ VMX-pi supports CAN but isn’t widely used. Copperforge’s CAN efforts remain pending. Lastly, Playing with Fusion released the Venom motor supporting CAN along with a time-of-flight sensor. 

---

posts.cooked: If I become a vendor, what do I need to do to get on the can bus?

posts.name: Carlos Gross Jones
posts.cooked: Email FIRST and convince them that you’re serious enough to deserve a CANbus manufacturer ID reservation. There’s nothing on the technical side that requires you to have your own ID. You could build a device that uses a manufacturer ID of, say, 100, and it’d work fine. The only thing that the official registry does is prevent address collisions.

posts.cooked:
You could build a device that uses a manufacturer ID of, say, 100, and it’d work fine. Right up until someone else had another device with ID=100 together with yours. The only thing that the official registry does is prevent address collisions. Exactly. If you’re not going to be registered, you should at least document your ID and ideally make it configurable.

posts.name: Justin Tervay
posts.cooked: Is 70% CAN Bus Utilization Bad? That’s one of the flaws with FRC’s CAN addressing scheme: the vendor packet priorities are essentially ordered by vendor ID, so all of CTRE’s PDP messages preempt REV’s motor controller messages, for instance. It’s a legacy partitioning scheme that originated from the CAN Jaguar; existing vendors have had to conform to it. REV, CTRE, and some others were looking into improving this at one point, but idk if it made it past the drawbridge.

link_counts.title: Is 70% CAN Bus Utilization Bad?

posts.name: Will Toth
posts.cooked:
On the CAN bus, messages from devices with lower IDs are prioritized over those with higher IDs when they are transmitted simultaneously or queued under the same conditions, assuming the queue is properly configured as a priority queue.

The device type field holds the highest priority weight. Consequently, any motor controller frame is given higher priority than any power distribution frame. Specifically, a CTRE Talon frame will always be prioritized above any PDP frame from any vendor. However, within the same device type, frames differ in priority: a Talon FX will outrank a SPARK MAX, which in turn will outrank a PwF Venom. Furthermore, among SPARK MAX units, those with lower device numbers gain precedence—so a SPARK MAX with ID 1 will have higher priority than one with ID 4. This setup ensures smooth operation but may require careful handling to avoid overload situations.

posts.name: s1900ahon
posts.cooked: The first version of the Message ID format and vendor assignments was developed in the summer of 2008 during the development of Jaguar’s v1 by Luminary Micro. In 2009, the CAN features were not permitted for use in FRC. DEKA received an assignment due to their role in introducing control systems components in 2009, specifically PDB, digital, and analog interfaces, which were designed by DEKA employee Eric VanWyk. Initially, there was hope DEKA could contribute to the FRC CAN ecosystem. Additionally, the Message ID format was conceptualized during FIRST coopertition, emphasizing that the vendor field wasn’t required if focused on a Jaguar-centric approach. Instead, the format aimed to recognize the potential benefits of CAN technology in the future, requiring cooperation among suppliers. Over more than 10 years, less than 16 vendors out of a maximum of 255 are assigned, with one assignment designated for team use.
